{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a69a3b1-d018-491b-b3d0-30555f0fafe5","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 broadened **implicit span conversions**. Arrays now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and overload resolution considers span-based extension methods. So `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\ninstead of the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, which expression trees cannot represent. The expression tree compiles, but the interpreted invocation fails at runtime because the span-based method can't be called through the expression tree infrastructure.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nForce the compiler back to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by either casting or calling it explicitly:\n\n**Option A — cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` directly (no extension syntax):**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth bypass the span-based overload and keep the expression tree representable. Option A is the smallest diff if you have many call sites.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c67a21f1-ba18-42fd-8d29-c3bf674859ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The key issue is about **params collections** and **`System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains`** vs **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`**.\n \nIn .NET 9, calling `Contains` on an array resolved to the LINQ extension method, but in .NET 10, the compiler now prefers the `MemoryExtensions` overload since arrays implicitly convert to `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes the method resolution order and can break expression trees that were compiled against the older LINQ method.\n\nThe real issue is that `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are ref structs and can't be represented in expression trees, so if the compiler picks the `MemoryExtensions` version, the expression tree fails at runtime when it tries to interpret the call. let me reconsider the timeline. In C# 13 / .NET 9, `params` was extended to support `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. And arrays got implicit conversions to spans. But the expression tree issue with spans...\n\nLet me think about this more carefully with what I know:\n\n1. In .NET 9, `array.Contains(value)` resolves to `Enumerable.Contains<T>()` which works fine in expression trees.\n\n2. In .NET 10 / C# 14, the compiler's overload resolution has changed. With the new implicit span conversions and extension type changes, `array.Contains(value)` may now resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.\n\n3. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and can't be used in expression trees, if the compiler picks this overload during expression tree construction, it would fail. Expression trees built from lambdas are validated at compile time for ref struct usage, so this should be a compile-time error. But the user reports a runtime exception, which makes me wonder if there's a different mechanism at play—maybe the expression tree is constructed manually, or there's something about how .NET 10 handles this that I'm not recalling correctly. So the real issue is that C# 14 now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` when you call `Contains` on an array, since `int[]` implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`. But expression trees can't contain ref structs like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which should trigger a compile-time error—yet the user says it throws at runtime, suggesting the compiler might not be catching it in all cases and the runtime fails during interpretation instead.\n\nThe workaround is to force the use of `Enumerable.Contains` directly, either by calling it explicitly, casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first, or using `AsEnumerable()` to bypass the span overload resolution. Actually wait - I want to make sure I'm right about the mechanism. Let me think again about what C# 14 changes cause this.\n\nC# 14 introduces first-class span types with implicit conversions from arrays. The key changes are:\n- `T[]` implicitly converts to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` (this existed before but was special-cased)\n- Overload resolution now considers these conversions more broadly\n- Extension method resolution considers span-based extensions\n\nSo when you have `array.Contains(num)` and both `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` and `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` are candidates:\n\nIn C# 13: Only `Enumerable.Contains` is considered (span conversion not in scope for extension method resolution)\nIn C# 14: Both are considered, and `MemoryExtensions.Contains` wins because `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is a more specific conversion than `int[]` → `IEnumerable<int>`\n\nThis means in C# 14, expression trees containing `array.Contains(num)` try to use `MemoryExtensions.Contains` which involves ref struct `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and this isn't representable in expression trees. The fix is to cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`.","outputTokens":2365},"id":"70e2b743-2f77-48b1-b529-e5f2de9acd26","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:31:34.462Z","parentId":"ed45c0d2-c06d-4c18-9b97-511af4e44a36"}
